1.0  IINTRODUCTION
A Risk Management Program (RMP) has been implemented at Beatrice Foods for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials. The RMP summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that work together to minimize the risk to the community of hazardous chemical releases. The Risk Management Plan is organized to correspond with specific U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) RMP definitions and requirements, including:
> Introduction;
> Beatrice policies to protect health, environment, and safety;
> Facility identification and regulated substances covered processes;
> Hazard Assessment;
> Prevention Program;
> Five-Year Accident History;
> Emergency Response Plan; and
> Planned changes to improve safety.

2.0  BEATRICE FOODS POLICIES TO PROTECT HEALTH, ENVIRONMENT, AND SAFETY

Risk management and safety are important concerns at Beatrice Foods; this RMP formalizes and documents these activities. Beatrice Foods is committed to conducting its operations in a safe and responsible manner and to reducing risks to human health and to the environment.

3.0  FACILITY IDENTIFICATION

The Beatrice Foods facility is located at 4300 West 62nd Street in Indianapolis, Indiana. The facility produces margarine products. The facility uses ammonia for refrigeration,  and is regulated under 40 CFR Part 68, the EPA RMP Rule. The amount of ammonia present in the refrigeration system is approximately 36,000 pounds, which is above the minimum threshold quantity of 10,000 pounds.  

